@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home";
}

<section class="hero-panel">
    <span class="eyebrow">Week 7 Project 02</span>
    <h1>Update only the part of the page that needs new data.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        This project demonstrates partial page updates with plain JavaScript. Each button targets a different section,
        so students can see replace and append behavior without a full refresh.
    </p>
    <div class="action-row">
        <a class="button button-primary" asp-page="/Dashboard">Open The Partial Updates Demo</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="/api/learningdashboard/announcements" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">View Sample JSON</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="card-grid">
    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>What students practise</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Target one DOM section at a time with Fetch API responses.</li>
            <li>Replace announcement content while leaving the form untouched.</li>
            <li>Append new activity entries below the existing list.</li>
            <li>Refresh summary cards independently from the rest of the page.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
        <h2>Why this example matters</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Students can see how page state survives when only one section updates.</li>
            <li>The difference between replace and append becomes easy to observe.</li>
            <li>The same backend can support several small page updates instead of one large reload.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>
</section>

<section class="info-panel">
    <h2>Suggested walkthrough</h2>
    <ol>
        <li>Load the dashboard and type into the reflection form.</li>
        <li>Refresh the announcements and confirm the form text stays in place.</li>
        <li>Submit a check-in and watch only the activity log grow.</li>
        <li>Refresh the summary cards separately to confirm the rest of the page stays unchanged.</li>
    </ol>
</section>
